User survey for ImagingSociety 2025 - National MRI research infrastructure in Norway

Author

Dr. Athanasia M. Mowinckel

Published

September 23, 2025

Background

This report presents an analysis of the survey data collected for the national grant scheme application for MRI research infrastructure in Norway. The survey was designed to gather insights from the research community on the current use, needs, and challenges related to MRI for human research.

The following sections will present a summary of the key findings, including graphical representations of the quantitative data and a textual summary of the open-ended responses, with the help of the Gemini LMM.

Survey Results

Of the 45 responses, 17 participants reported they currently use MRI for research, 38% indicate a future interest in using the new MRI facility for their work.

Participant Demographics

This section provides an overview of the survey participants’ roles and institutions.

Research Areas

The survey respondents represent a diverse range of research areas, but cognitive neuroscience is the most prominent. Other significant areas include neuroscience (broadly defined), mental health research (including disorders, psychotherapy, and child/adolescent psychiatry), aging and dementia research, and specific neurological conditions like multiple sclerosis and brain injury. There’s also representation in areas like women’s health, language processing, brain imaging techniques, and more specialized fields like music cognition, environmental psychology, and paleoclimatology. In summary, the responses lean heavily towards cognitive and clinical neuroscience, with a strong emphasis on brain function, mental health, and neurological disorders.

How MRI Would Enhance Research

Based on the survey responses, expanded access to MRI would significantly improve research in several key areas:

  • Neurological and Psychiatric Disorders: Enhanced MRI access would facilitate research into a wide range of conditions, including ADHD, dementia (Alzheimer’s, Lewy body), SLE (lupus nephritis), multiple sclerosis (MS), eating disorders, and neurodevelopmental disorders. This includes understanding the structural and functional brain changes associated with these conditions, identifying potential biomarkers, and evaluating the effectiveness of interventions.
  • Cognitive Neuroscience: MRI would enable deeper investigations into cognitive processes such as memory, attention, executive functions, language (bilingualism), emotion regulation, and decision-making. Researchers could explore the neural networks underlying these processes and how they change across the lifespan (aging) and under different conditions (e.g., hormonal fluctuations, menopause).
  • Sexual Function and Arousal: Access to MRI would allow researchers to investigate the brain’s involvement in normal and deviant sexual arousal, sexual decision-making, partner attraction, and sexual preferences.
  • Brain Stimulation and Interventions: Researchers use MRI to examine the underlying mechanisms of non-invasive brain stimulation in general and the underlying mechanisms of non-invasive brain stimulation as a treatment for clinical disorders in particular.
  • Basic Brain Function: It would open possibilities for looking at brain network involved in cognition.
  • Impact of Sex and Hormones on the Brain: Access to MRI would allow studies to be made between anatomical and functional brain differences between males and females. It would allow studies to understand how hormonal functions influence these differences.
  • Methodological Advancements: More accessible MRI would foster the development of novel MRI sequences and image analysis techniques.
  • Clinical Translation: MRI provides clinically relevant information for decision making, tracking of disease progression and the development of novel algorithms that can be tested and validated in a hospital setting.
  • Geohazard Study: It would represent a new technique to “diagnose” geohazard in the afore-mentioned geological archives.

Common Themes and Benefits:

  • Increased Sample Sizes and Statistical Power: More access allows researchers to conduct larger, well-powered studies.
  • Multicenter Collaborations: Reliable access facilitates participation in multicenter studies, leading to more robust and generalizable findings.
  • Improved Data Quality and Specificity: High-performance fMRI and advanced sequences enhance the quality and precision of research.
  • Enhanced Research Opportunities: Researchers can pursue new research questions, gain experience, and secure funding by including MRI components in their studies.
  • Clinical Relevance: MRI findings can inform clinical decision-making, track disease progression, and personalize treatment approaches.
  • Addressing Health Disparities: Increased MRI availability in underserved regions like northern Norway enables more equitable access to research and clinical care.

Key Barriers and Desired Improvements:

  • Limited Access: The primary obstacle is the lack of readily available MRI slots.
  • Cost: High costs restrict research opportunities.
  • Infrastructure and Expertise: A need for organizational models that support researcher-led scanner management and access to neuroradiologists for clinical assessments.
  • Flexibility: Need for flexibility in scheduling, particularly for studies involving hormonal cycles.
  • Scanner Specifications: Requirements for improved scanner specifications and access to the most advanced sequences.

Future Needs

This section analyzes which conditions are considered most important for the future of MRI research in Norway.

Summary of Free-text Comments

This section provides a summary of the open-ended comments, generated using the Gemini LMM.

Several key themes emerge from the feedback regarding MRI research conditions. A strong desire for dedicated research MRI facilities located closer to the University of Bergen campus, rather than within the hospital, is evident, implying a preference for prioritizing research over clinical use and potentially leading to suggestions for adjusted pricing models. The establishment of a collaborative MRI research community in Tromsø is also seen as crucial, emphasizing the importance of knowledge sharing and joint initiatives. Finally, the acknowledgement of existing infrastructure improvements (UIO scanner upgrades) and relevant organizations (MMIV) suggests a need for better integration and leveraging of current resources within a wider, collaborative framework.

Conclusion

The findings of this survey resoundingly underscore a critical need for increased investment in dedicated research-focused MRI scanners across Norway. While the existing clinical scanners serve a vital purpose, their limitations in availability, advanced capabilities, and dedicated research support are demonstrably hindering the progress of Norwegian neuroscience, medical imaging, and related fields. The passionate and detailed responses from researchers across diverse institutions and disciplines – from psychology and linguistics to neurology and psychiatry – paint a clear picture of a community eager to leverage cutting-edge MRI technology to unlock new insights into the human brain and body.

The benefits are multifaceted, ranging from enabling participation in large-scale, multi-center studies and attracting international collaborations to fostering innovation in treatment strategies and attracting and retaining talented researchers. By addressing the identified gaps in infrastructure, Norway can empower its scientific community to conduct more robust, cutting-edge research, ultimately leading to improved diagnostics, therapies, and a deeper understanding of health and disease. This investment isn’t merely about acquiring hardware; it’s about fostering a thriving research ecosystem that benefits the scientific community, the healthcare system, and, most importantly, the people of Norway. The time for strategic action is now to ensure Norway remains at the forefront of biomedical research and innovation.
